<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="358" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1259]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,874,899]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Remarks.</emphasis>
The shades of pallid brown coloration reported by Golovatch 
<emphasis box="[1009,1057,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">et al</emphasis>
. (2004) is the faded pigmentation after 18 years in preservative; we suspect that the varying shades were actually black to gray in life. Despite fading, the dorsal color pattern can still be discerned, and the millipede appears to be uniformly dark middorsally with narrow, lighter bands along the anterior and caudal metatergal margins (
<figureCitation box="[981,1069,982,1007]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1931,1953]" captionTargetBox="[210,1370,197,1907]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[207,1376,193,1911]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Somatic featUres of Xanthotropis media n. comb. A. Head and left antenna, anterior View (right antenna missing). B. CollUm and tergites 2–3, dorsal View. C. Right paranota of rings 2–4, dorsal View; the red arrows denote the anterolateral teeth. D. Rings 17–19 and telson, dorsal View. Scale lines: 1.00 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439776/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
) connecting with the broad and substantially lighter paranotal markings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1259]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeekel" authorityYear="2000" box="[199,366,1056,1079]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Haematotropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,366,1056,1079]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Haematotropis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is defined by the small anterolateral teeth on paranota 2–4 and the elongated acropodital femur (
<figureCitation box="[159,255,1090,1115]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[275,1327,204,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[234,1368,196,1864]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gonopodal configUrations of select aphelidesmine genera showing relatiVe lengths of the telopodital prefemora and acropodite. A. Aphelidesmus, A. junki GoloVatch, Hoffman &amp; Spelda, 2004, right gonopod, lateral View. B. Ochrotropis, O. guianensis (Chamberlin, 1923), left gonopod, lateral View (modified from Jeekel, 2000). C. Haematotropis, H. callipa (Peters, 1864), right gonopod, medial View. Scale lines: 1.00 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439774/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Almeida &amp; Shelley &amp; Rafael" authorityYear="2018" box="[281,452,1090,1115]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" rank="subSpecies" status="n. comb." subSpecies="media">
That 
<emphasis box="[346,452,1091,1115]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">X. media</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[467,575,1090,1115]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[467,575,1090,1115]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">n. comb.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
possesses such features explains the original assignment, but based on gonopodal similarities, the authors also suggested placement in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brolemann" authorityYear="1898" box="[913,1069,1127,1151]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Aphelidesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[913,1069,1127,1151]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Aphelidesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We conclude that its external features and the gonopodal configuration are sufficiently different from the patterns in both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeekel" authorityYear="2000" box="[1219,1386,1163,1186]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Haematotropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1219,1386,1163,1186]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Haematotropis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brolemann" authorityYear="1898" box="[151,307,1199,1223]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Aphelidesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,307,1199,1223]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Aphelidesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that generic distinction is warranted and therefore establish 
<taxonomicName authority="Almeida &amp; Shelley &amp; Rafael, 2018" authorityName="Almeida &amp; Shelley &amp; Rafael" authorityYear="2018" box="[985,1130,1199,1223]" class="Diplopoda" family="Aphelidesmidae" genus="Xanthotropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[985,1130,1199,1223]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Xanthotropis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1138,1217,1198,1223]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1138,1217,1198,1223]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, which is presently monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
